<font color="#FF0000">HONORING A WORTHY FOE</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jul 23 20:14:15 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Worthy Foes<br>
Amazing, when we talk of love and war, death and destruction, life and happiness we so often forget of the enemy's families and friends.  Their duties and responsibilities, honors and achievements.<br><br>
On the morning of May 4th, 1968, I was lying on the ground facing toward where intelligence had said the enemy would be coming from. We had set up an ambush at the bottom of Hill 65.<br><br>
Robb (Charles Robb) was on the hill behind us, since his arrival as our company's CO, they wouldn't allow two platoons to go out together, because if they did the Captain would have to go.<br>
It's Marine Corps policy that an officer must be where the majority of his men are. <br>
If the majority of his men are out in the field then the commanding officer is suppose to be out there as well. Fear of his capture by the enemy prevented our engaging the enemy, as we should have. <br>
Often instead of being out in force, squads or a platoon would be out where a platoon or a company force should have been.  Charlie knew this and took advantage of it, planting more mines and bobby traps then he ever had before. <br><br>
As we settled in, that night, I told my M-79 men to watch our backs.  Since Hill 65 was there, it didn't seems likely the enemy would choose to travel in-between the road we were covering and the hill behind us, but just in case, I had said, keep your eyes open in that direction as well. <br><br>
Early that morning he nudged me to point out that a column of about 15 men were moving toward us. <br>
Since there were ARVN's in the area and the gooks were walking in a column, he felt they were friendlies walking in between our positions. <br><br>
It was a dark night, barely enough light to give shape to plants, trees and the ever present unfamiliar objects all around us. By then the soldiers had came up on us and the tall one in front had turned and was trying to figure out what was the form laying at his feet. <br><br>
As I looked up his trousers legs, my eyes quickly focused the dark Red Chinese Communist Star belt buckle. <br>
I opened up, and clearly heard the sound of death as it snatched his life away. We scrambled then to open up on the others and at the same time, the rest of squad to our left opened up.  <br>
We were by then, completely surrounded by the enemy and no one knew where they were and they didn't know where we were. Chaos ensued as they scrambled for safety by either running by the other Marines or by withdrawing to where they had come from. Within seconds three more of the enemies dead laid by us. They had been wasted by my automatic riflemen and the M-79 men who dropped his as they fled. <br><br>
When daylight came, we searched the enemy's bodies for documents and identification. The NVA lieutenant I had killed had a wallet full of pictures. They mostly were of his family. His wife and children, grand parents and others from China. <br><br>
Behind the picture was an officially stamped certificate. <br><br>
QUAN AQI GIM PHONG MIEN NAM VIETNAM<br>
GIAYKHEN<br>
Comrade…..<br><br>
Translated it begins,<br><br>
South Vietnam Liberation Armed Forces<br>
Certificate of Commendation<br>
Awarded to Comrade…….<br><br>
It was a commendation to the Chinese I had killed. He had been promoted to the rank of a lieutenant  or company commander for having killed a Marine Corps Corporal and for having captured that Marines machine gun. <br><br>
I guess it was there and then, that I made piece with the world and with the war and I knew beyond a doubt that I was fighting a just cause.<br><br>
Today, on Hill 65 and Hill 37 from where we ran our daily patrols, operations and mission, huge red, blue and yellow colored pillars decorate the top of those hills. They were erected in honor of their war dead. Many women's names appear on the cement blocks especially on Hill 65. A lot of them fought against us with deadly conviction.<br><br>
While those large monuments and war memorials were erected to honor their brave soldiers they are also a memorial in honor of us, because without us as a worthy foe they would not have received such honor.<br><br>
I am Cook Barela and those are my thoughts.<br><br>

<p><code>-- In War and Peace  (Cook Barela) </code><p>


